Jessie Barry and Chris Wood. Walking around the pond. Warm. Humid. 70F. Calm. Clear.

A cold, rainy morning at Myers scoping with Charles.  The best observations were of Common Mergansers courting in the protected bay of the Myers marina, 4 males and 1 female performing kick and tail-up displays while vocalizing as well as 3 Gadwall, 2 males and 1 female which were performing an interesting kick display, also vocalizing, (cool nasal honk).  This is the first time I have really had the chance to pay close attention to the COME display and the first time I have seen a GAWA display.

column23: Montezuma NWR--Mays Point Pool and road
column46: Mike Andersen, Jesse Ellis, Scott Haber, Pete Hosner, Dan Lebbin, and I headed up to Montezuma yesterday --afternoon, where we eventually bumped into Meena Haribal, Kevin and Jay McGowan, and even a wayward Irishman Gerard Phillips.  --    First, the big news from Montezuma is that Mays Point Pool was --literally drained overnight.  Mays was mostly full of water on Saturday --morning, but when we arrived yesterday, there were mudflats everywhere!  --There was also a significant influx of new shorebirds at Mays, compared --with what we saw on Saturday morning, and what was reported on Saturday --evening.  Most impressive of all was the presence of 18 BAIRD''S --SANDPIPERS, a total that equals the high count for New York State and --represents a new non-coastal maximum.  The Baird''s Sandpipers were mixed --in with numbers of LEAST, SEMIPALMATED, and PECTORAL SANDPIPERS, and --often afforded great views on the nearest mudflat to the right of the --coral.  Besides the big influx of new Baird''s, other new shorebird --arrivals in the past 24 hours included four SHORT-BILLED DOWITCHERS, three --STILT SANDPIPERS (with one still almost completely barred), one WILSON''S --SNIPE (formerly Common Snipe), and one molting adult BLACK-BELLIED --PLOVER.  GREATER YELLOWLEGS and LESSER YELLOWLEGS were both present, as --were KILLDEER, thirty SEMIPALMATED PLOVERS (~25 adults to 5 juveniles), --and one SPOTTED SANDPIPER.      --    As if these shorebirds weren''t enough, there was a LEAST BITTERN --extravaganza at Montezuma yesterday.  Our original group of six from --Ithaca did a quick trip through the Auto Loop, where, thanks to Mark --Chao''s excellent description, we were able to find three Least Bitterns --in the area across from marker 1 on the Auto Loop.  Two birds were --adults, while the third was a still-partially-downy juvenile bird.  Then, --almost as soon as we arrived at Mays, Mike spotted an immature --BLACK-CROWNED NIGHT-HERON, a GREEN HERON, and a LEAST BITTERN almost in a --row in the canal stretching from Mays Point Pool towards Tschache Pool.  --Eventually, I saw three different Least Bitterns, and I think somebody --might have seen a fourth.  Also in that area, Meena picked out a black --fluffball (this is one of Meena''s specialties) that turned out to be a --VIRGINIA RAIL chick.  Granted, all rail chicks are black fluffballs, but --we felt confident with that identification, since this black fluffball --was accompanied by first one, and then two, adult VIRGINIA RAILS.  --     Alas, before the McGowan boys and Gerard arrived, the seven of us --were treated to a show by a MERLIN that zoomed through Mays several --times.  Meena just made mention a few days ago to locating raptors by the --chatter of swallows in the area, and that was exactly how I first noticed --the presence of the Merlin.  We were eventually able to watch this bird --for an extended period of time (5 minutes?) as it chased after the --smallest shorebirds.  It seemed to have a single bird singled out and --away from the main flock a few times, but it was never successful in --actually catching anything.  Eventually, it was "escorted" out of the --area by a group of swallows.    --    The final highlight of the evening was a brief appearance of a --COMMON NIGHTHAWK flying over Mays at exactly 8 pm.  Because of a --relatively heavy cloud cover, it was fairly dark at this point, and the --13 GREAT EGRETS that had been in Mays had already left for their roosting --spot (which we decided was somewhere in the direction of Tschache Pool).  --Earlier in the evening, there were also 13 CASPIAN TERNS (including one --juvenile) at Mays.

column46: Overcast, with light snow falling; wind NNW at 10 mph; 22* F. Several inches of snow on the ground, including 1-2 inches of fresh now. Took the standard side jaunt to the end of the service road (leading to the water tower site) just south of Sanctuary Drive. Otherwise walked the entire way along Sapsucker Woods Road. At the Lab, stepped into the Morgens Observatory for a quick look at the pond and the Treman Bird-feeding Garden; then stepped back outside, continued north, and entered the Lab at the staff entrance. Mammals: Eastern Gray Squirrel (9), Red Squirrel (1| heard).
South Nassau CBC, the birds I personally saw anyway.

GREATER YELLOWLEGS and LESSER YELLOWLEGS were both present, as --were KILLDEER, thirty SEMIPALMATED PLOVERS (~25 adults to 5 juveniles), --and one SPOTTED SANDPIPER.      --    As if these shorebirds weren''t enough, there was a LEAST BITTERN --extravaganza at Montezuma yesterday.  Our original group of six from --Ithaca did a quick trip through the Auto Loop, where, thanks to Mark --Chao''s excellent description, we were able to find three Least Bitterns --in the area across from marker 1 on the Auto Loop.  Two birds were --adults, while the third was a still-partially-downy juvenile bird.  Then, --almost as soon as we arrived at Mays, Mike spotted an immature --BLACK-CROWNED NIGHT-HERON, a GREEN HERON, and a LEAST BITTERN almost in a --row in the canal stretching from Mays Point Pool towards Tschache Pool.  --Eventually, I saw three different Least Bitterns, and I think somebody --might have seen a fourth.  Also in that area, Meena picked out a black --fluffball (this is one of Meena''s specialties) that turned out to be a --VIRGINIA RAIL chick.  Granted, all rail chicks are black fluffballs, but --we felt confident with that identification, since this black fluffball --was accompanied by first one, and then two, adult VIRGINIA RAILS.  --     Alas, before the McGowan boys and Gerard arrived, the seven of us --were treated to a show by a MERLIN that zoomed through Mays several --times.  Meena just made mention a few days ago to locating raptors by the --chatter of swallows in the area, and that was exactly how I first noticed --the presence of the Merlin.  We were eventually able to watch this bird --for an extended period of time (5 minutes?) as it chased after the --smallest shorebirds.  It seemed to have a single bird singled out and --away from the main flock a few times, but it was never successful in --actually catching anything.  Eventually, it was "escorted" out of the --area by a group of swallows.    --    The final highlight of the evening was a brief appearance of a --COMMON NIGHTHAWK flying over Mays at exactly 8 pm.  Because of a --relatively heavy cloud cover, it was fairly dark at this point, and the --13 GREAT EGRETS that had been in Mays had already left for their roosting --spot (which we decided was somewhere in the direction of Tschache Pool).  --Earlier in the evening, there were also 13 CASPIAN TERNS (including one --juvenile) at Mays.

Partly cloudy; calm initially, then a light S wind at 6 mph; 74-76* F (according to the National Weather Service at Ithaca Tompkins Regional Airport; our RadioShack thermometer at home, positioned just below the nest box at the edge of the woods behind the house, read only 68*F when I left at 08:00, although the temperature was rising rapidly). Took the standard side jaunt to the end of the service road (leading to the water tower site) just south of Sanctuary Drive, and also entered the area around the Frog Barn, to the edge of the Frog Barn pond. From the Frog Barn, walked through the woods along the southwestern segment of the East Trail to Sapsucker Woods Road. I crossed the road, reentered Sapsucker Woods, and continued along the eastern segments of the Severinghaus and Wilson trails, including the Podell Boardwalk. At the Lab, stepped into the Morgens Observatory for a quick look at the pond and the Treman Bird-feeding Garden. I then stepped back outside, and continued north. I checked again (and again unsuccessfully) for Virginia Rail in the wetlands between the service entrance and the Lab parking lots. I entered the Lab at the staff entrance. Daylight Saving Time. Mammals: Eastern Cottontail (1), Eastern Gray Squirrel (6), Eastern Chipmunk (5).
4 ESOW playbacks

It had been far too long since we had done this walk (this was the first time in July!). Ran into a couple interesting flocks of birds. Perhaps the most interesting birds were two different MYRTLE WARBLERS. It seems very likely that these were molt migrants since they do not breed at Monkey Run (at least this part). WEATHER: Very humid. 82 - 85F. Calm. Overcast. OBSERVERS: Chris Wood and Jessie Barry.

Mostly clear to partly cloudy; calm; 56-63* F. Casual observations from the driveway, and from inside the house looking out over the back yard and the bird feeders behind the house, and over the Cornell fields opposite to the house, across Hanshaw Road. The wheat field along Hanshaw Road now is completely harvested. Feeders up: sunflower (almost empty), niger; also hummingbird feeder (under eaves by kitchen window, and in maple), orange holder for orioles. Daylight Saving Time. Overcast, with intermittent light sleet; wind NW at 15-22 mph; 36* F. Sapsucker Woods Road and trails through the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary, from the south border of the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary just north of 67 Sapsucker Woods Road (excluding areas outside of the Sanctuary west of Sapsucker Woods Road, from Sanctuary Drive north to 260 Sapsucker Woods Road) north to the Cornell Lab of Ornithology. I entered the area around the Frog Barn, to the edge of the Frog Barn pond. From the Frog Barn, I walked through the woods along the southwestern segment of the East Trail to Sapsucker Woods Road, crossed the road, and continued along the eastern segments of the Severinghaus and Wilson trails, including the boardwalk. Water levels high under the boardwalk (higher, at least, than they've been so far this spring.)  At the Lab, I stepped into the observatory for a look at the pond and the bird feeding garden. I then went upstairs and viewed the pond again from the observatory on the second floor (between the library and the administration offices). Returning downstairs, I exited through the caterer's entrance, on the east side of the Lab, and continued north, entering the Lab again at the staff entrance at the northeast corner of the building. Thursday. Eastern Daylight Saving Time. Mammals: Eastern Gray Squirrel (1).

Sapsucker Woods Road and trails through the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary, from the south border of the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary just north of 67 Sapsucker Woods Road (excluding areas outside of the Sanctuary west of Sapsucker Woods Road, from Sanctuary Drive north to 260 Sapsucker Woods Road) north to the Cornell Lab of Ornithology. I entered the area around the Frog Barn, to the edge of the Frog Barn pond. From the Frog Barn, I walked through the woods along the southwestern segment of the East Trail to Sapsucker Woods Road, crossed the road, and continued along the eastern segments of the Severinghaus and Wilson trails, including the boardwalk. Water levels high under the boardwalk (higher, at least, than they've been so far this spring.)  At the Lab, I stepped into the observatory for a look at the pond and the bird feeding garden. I then went upstairs and viewed the pond again from the observatory on the second floor (between the library and the administration offices). Returning downstairs, I exited through the caterer's entrance, on the east side of the Lab, and continued north, entering the Lab again at the staff entrance at the northeast corner of the building. column23: Salt Marsh Nature Center at Marine Park
column46: What at first seemed like madness on this very hot and humid morning became a surprisingly enjoyable walk through the restored area, thanks to sufficient breezes, an absence of biting insects, and  enough birds to keep us distracted.  Highlights included an Oystercatcher "drama" wherein the quite active chick was temporarily separated from its parents, who spent quite some time running up and down the path and vocalizing (as only AMOYs can do) until the eventual reunion.  One of the younger killdeer chicks was seen with the adults,  at some distance from  spraying activities in their usual area.  One osprey was seen on the platform, then gliding overhead.  More unusually, one of our sharper-eyed birders caught a brief look at three flying bobolinks before they disappeared into the Spartina.

Mostly cloudy (visibility 10.0 miles); wind S to SE at 10 mph; 47-48 F. Light rain began yesterday afternoon, and continued until dawn. Ground bare (no snow cover). Deciduous trees are bare. Sapsucker Woods Road and trails through the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary, from the south border of the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary just north of 67 Sapsucker Woods Road (excluding areas outside of the Sanctuary west of Sapsucker Woods Road, from Sanctuary Drive north to 260 Sapsucker Woods Road) north to the Cornell Lab of Ornithology. I entered the area around the "Frog Barn" (91 Sapsucker Woods Road), to the edge of the Frog Barn pond (which remains frozen). From the Frog Barn, I returned to Sapsucker Woods Road and continued north along the road to the Lab. At the Lab, I stepped into the observatory for a quick look at the pond and the bird-feeding garden. The pond is mostly frozen, but the usual open area in front of the observatory (maintained all winter by the bubbler) has expanded greatly in size; the ice elsewhere on the pond is covered with water, making it difficult to identify open areas at a distance. I stepped outside again, continuing north and entering the Lab at the northeast corner of the building. Other bird feeders along this route: 143 Sapsucker Woods Road (suet; seed feeders inactive?), 151 Sapsucker Woods Road. Friday. Civil twilight begins 06:55; sunrise 07:25; sunset 17:13; civil twilight ends 17:43. Eastern Standard Time. Mammals: Eastern Gray Squirrel (11).

column23: Nate's Patch--Bluegrass to Hanshaw to Freese
column46: Mostly clear; wind W at 6 mph, shifting to N at 7 mph; 68-70* F. Casual observations while Michi and I took Rufus for a walk. We left home (1462 Hanshaw Road) and headed east on Hanshaw, then south on Freese Road. Just south of Dyce Lab, we turned west on the unpaved track that leads to the east edge of the Equine Research Park woods. At the woods, we turned south until we intersected the track that extends west from Liddell Lab. We headed west, and then, at the edge of the Equine Research Park complex, turned south and entered the woods along Fall Creek (separate eBird checklist). We returned home the same way we came, so the reported distance traveled is only half the distance that we walked. Field conditions: The field along Hanshaw Road, between Bluegrass and Freese, has a grain crop (winter wheat?) that now is over two feet tall. As usual, the small (ca  3.52 acres) field at the corner of Hanshaw and Freese is uncultivated, and is covered in tall grass. Also as usual, the field (ca 5.38 acres) across Freese Road from Dyce Lab is uncultivated; this field is a mix of herbaceous growth, but presumably will be dominated by goldenrod in the fall. The larger field (ca 10.50 acres) just southwest of Dyce Lab (on the west side of Freese Road; bordered to the south by the unpaved track that leads to the Equine Research Park woods), has low growth of a broad-leaved crop, which I don't recognize at this stage. The large (ca 15.87 acres) field to the south of this track (and across Freese Road from the north end of the Freese Community Gardens), which yesterday was tall mix of grass and herbaceous growth, is being cut today. The field (ca 10 acres) across Freese Road from the south end of the Freese Community Gardens (and just north of Liddell Labs) has the same broad-leaved crop as in the field southwest of Dyce Lab. Sunday. Eastern Daylight Saving Time. Mammals: none observed?
Even the Crows were quiet this morning.

A breezy afternoon walk around the Wilson trail, CLO inner parking lot, into the goldenrod on the hill near Kip's Barn, (where I flushed the Palm Warbler), and over to the powerline trail.  The White-crowned Sparrow was a juvenile pished up from the wet woods at the edge of the short section of boardwalk heading north to the fire pond.  My first White-crowned Sparrow for the season.

column23: Salt Marsh Nature Center at Marine Park
column46: A very interesting summer walk in the restoration area, led by visiting Sergeant Ranger Tony and joined by Urban Park Ranger Fellows Lee, Nicole, and Carlos (as well as Ranger Christina in civilian mode).  Recent flooding forced us to backtrack instead of completing the loop as usual, but there were still many rewarding sightings. Today's highlights, though, were "off-list"--a most unusual bird later ID'd as a presumed escapee White-tailed Diamond Dove, and, for our second diamond, a Diamond-Backed Terrapin seen covering her nest in a wide spot in the gravel trail; DBT's are often seen in the marsh and basking, but none of us had ever encountered one nesting at this location.  Lots of butterflies, too, including Monarchs, Black Swallowtails, Sulphurs,  a Common Sootywing, and several unidentified skippers.

column23: Salt Marsh Nature Center at Marine Park
column46: What at first seemed like madness on this very hot and humid morning became a surprisingly enjoyable walk through the restored area, thanks to sufficient breezes, an absence of biting insects, and  enough birds to keep us distracted.  Highlights included an Oystercatcher "drama" wherein the quite active chick was temporarily separated from its parents, who spent quite some time running up and down the path and vocalizing (as only AMOYs can do) until the eventual reunion.  One of the younger killdeer chicks was seen with the adults,  at some distance from  spraying activities in their usual area.  One osprey was seen on the platform, then gliding overhead.  More unusually, one of our sharper-eyed birders caught a brief look at three flying bobolinks before they disappeared into the Spartina.

Overcast; windy, S at 15 mph; 53* F. Took the standard side jaunts to the end of the service road (leading to the water tower site) just south of Sanctuary Drive, and to the edge of the small pond at the Frog Barn. From the Frog Barn area, walked through the woods along the southwestern segment of the East Trail to Sapsucker Woods Road; crossed the road, and continued through the woods along the eastern segments of the Severinghaus and Wilson trails, including the Podell Boardwalk. At the Lab, stepped into the Morgens Observatory for a quick look at the pond and the Treman Bird-feeding Garden; then stepped back outside, continued north, and entered the Lab at the staff entrance. Mammals: Eastern Gray Squirrel (8), Red Squirrel (1| heard).

The original eBird list only includes birds seen by TCL. Also reported were:--Common Nighthawk - 1--Ruby-crowned Kinglet (possible) - 1--American Pipit - 1--Northern Parula - 4--Bay-breasted Warbler - 1--"Baypoll" Warbler - 1--Mourning Warbler - 1 (male)--Connecticut Warbler - 1 (male seen in flight over the field)--House Sparrow - 1----Please adjust your list to align with the birds you remember observing.----Tom Johnson's post to CAYUGABIRDS---------Whew...After the stadium light banks were turned out just before 12:50 am, Mike Harvey, Tim Lenz, and I tallied up estimated (some are exact) counts for the evening.  ~42 species were recorded, with highlights in Upland Sandpiper, Cape May Warbler, Mourning Warbler, Connecticut Warbler, and Dickcissels.----These numbers are a mix of what we heard and saw... I should add that there were so many birds overhead that it was very difficult to mentally filter flight calls and look for birds on the ground/ in the trees... Most of the birds on the turf were Savannah Sparrows, with a few Bobolinks and Common Yellowthroats mixed in.  For a few notes on identifying birds visually at night... it can be quite tough to get good looks with the bright stadium lights providing intense unnatural illumination, but we had success in picking out Black-throated Blue Warblers, Canada Warblers, Northern Parulas, Ovenbirds, Magnolia Warblers, and a few others in flight.  However, for every bird I got a nice look at, countless others zipped by as brown and yellow blurs.----I recorded a good portion of the night's flight with a microphone sitting out on top of Mike Harvey's car... apparently the first couple of hours were not saved before my laptop battery died, so I need to work on recovering that file.  However, I have an hour and ten minutes of solid flight call insanity from the end of the evening's "stadium flight". During the majority of this time (11:30 pm - 12:40 am), we were hearing probably over 5 calls per second (potentially quite a few more than that). There was a noticeable dropoff in calling as soon as the lights were turned off, and within 5 minutes of the lights being shut off, we were--hearing single calls perhaps once every 3-5 seconds... the draw that the stadium lights have on migrants seems to be pretty amazing. Throughout the evening we kept hearing odd "tee-tee-tee-tee" calls that sounded reminiscent of both a woodpecker and a shorebird... we figured that they were probably Ruddy Turnstones, and comparison of two calls recorded tonight to turnstone recordings I have on my computer seems to support that.----I was pretty amazed by the number of birds dropping into and around the stadium tonight... highlights for me were the Upland Sandpiper that called as I was getting off my bike just after arriving at the stadium, great looks at the Cape May Warbler, and the mind-blowing flyby male Connecticut Warbler.  Thanks to the 14+ birders who came out and helped find birds...----TBJ

Cooler. Overcast; calm initially, then a light (3 mph) W wind; 56-57* F. Schulenberg home at 1462 Hanshaw Road. The winter wheat in the field along Hanshaw Road now is over two feet high. Casual observations from the driveway, from the back deck, and from inside the house looking out over the back yard and the bird feeders behind the house, and over the Cornell fields opposite to the house, across Hanshaw Road. Windows closed because of the chill. Feeders up: sunflower, niger, and hummingbird in the east maple, safflower in the west maple, and hummingbird feeder under the eaves outside the kitchen window. Monday. Eastern Daylight Saving Time. Mammals: Eastern Gray Squirrel (2), Eastern Chipmunk (1).

column23: USDA Nut. Lab and Trail Behind
column46: Birded behind my building from 0900-0930 h this morning mostly looking down into Mundy from the K-permitted lot on Plantations Rd. behind the Plant Pathology greenhouses.  Lots of activity in the open sunlit area with Robins and Waxwings dominating.  Pee-Wee and Carolina Wren singing.  Highlights were a Scarlet Tanager male showing irregular patches of scarlet on the mostly greenish-yellow breast and a stunning male Hooded Warbler seen at about 10 yards.   In addition, I watched a warbler foraging farther down in the gorge--olive-yellow above, yellow breast and belly, a noticeable white on tail visible from above, no eye ring or wing-bars- female Hooded Warbler??)

However, for every bird I got a nice look at, countless others zipped by as brown and yellow blurs.----I recorded a good portion of the night's flight with a microphone sitting out on top of Mike Harvey's car... apparently the first couple of hours were not saved before my laptop battery died, so I need to work on recovering that file.  However, I have an hour and ten minutes of solid flight call insanity from the end of the evening's "stadium flight". During the majority of this time (11:30 pm - 12:40 am), we were hearing probably over 5 calls per second (potentially quite a few more than that). There was a noticeable dropoff in calling as soon as the lights were turned off, and within 5 minutes of the lights being shut off, we were--hearing single calls perhaps once every 3-5 seconds... the draw that the stadium lights have on migrants seems to be pretty amazing. Throughout the evening we kept hearing odd "tee-tee-tee-tee" calls that sounded reminiscent of both a woodpecker and a shorebird... we figured that they were probably Ruddy Turnstones, and comparison of two calls recorded tonight to turnstone recordings I have on my computer seems to support that.----I was pretty amazed by the number of birds dropping into and around the stadium tonight... highlights for me were the Upland Sandpiper that called as I was getting off my bike just after arriving at the stadium, great looks at the Cape May Warbler, and the mind-blowing flyby male Connecticut Warbler.  Thanks to the 14+ birders who came out and helped find birds...----TBJ

The Lesser Black-backed Gull was bigger than the Ring-billed Gulls and small than the Herring Gulls, it had bright yellow legs and the mantel was a darker gray than the other gulls. I have photos but the bird was distant and the photos are blurry. The bird was an adult with a bright yellow bill.
2nd day the gulls showed up. Other birds returned when they left. The bluebirds started a nest, but no eggs yet.

Clear; light breeze, E to SE at 3 mph; 54-57* F. Was joined at the north end of Sapsucker Woods Road by Nate Senner and Mark Chao. Took the standard side jaunts to the end of the service road (leading to the water tower site) just south of Sanctuary Drive, and to the edge of the small pond at the Frog Barn. Walked the entire way along Sapsucker Woods Road (rather than following trails through part of the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary). At the Lab, stepped into the Morgens Observatory for a quick look at the pond and the Treman Bird-feeding Garden; then stepped back outside, continued north, and entered the Lab at the staff entrance. Mammals: house cat (3), White-tailed Deer (2, does), Eastern Chipmunk (6), Red Squirrel (3) Eastern Gray Squirrel (8)
A bit overcast this morning, not too much around.
Submitted from BirdLog NA for iOS, version 1.5.1

Clear (visibility 10.0 miles); wind E at 3 mph, becoming calm; 61-69 F. The corn in the field along Hanshaw Road averages 3-4 feet tall. I followed the standard route, from home (1462 Hanshaw Road) east to Sapsucker Woods Road, and then north on Sapsucker Woods Road to the border of the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary. Deviations from Sapsucker Woods Road were to the edge of the Briarwood II woods ("Sapsucker Woods South"), up the intended road between 128 and 202 Sapsucker Woods Road; to the end of the service road (leading to the water tower site) just south of Sanctuary Drive; and up the short brush-lined track (former intended road?) between 246 and 254 Sapsucker Woods Road. Visible bird feeders along this route: 1466 Hanshaw Road (back yard), 31 Sapsucker Woods Road (inactive), 222 Sapsucker Woods Road (back yard; inactive), 226 Sapsucker Woods Road (hummingbird and seed feeders under the eaves), 238 Sapsucker Woods Road (feeder down), 81/82 Sanctuary Drive (back yard; down?; visible from the short brush lined track north of Sanctuary Drive), and 260 Sapsucker Woods Road. There also may be feeders at 15 Sapsucker Woods Road, where no feeders are visible from road, but there often are birds here and I suspect feeders. Wednesday. Civil twilight begins 05:05; sunrise 05:39; sunset 20:43; civil twilight ends 21:17. Eastern Daylight Saving Time. Mammals: Eastern Gray Squirrel (2), Red Squirrel (3| heard), Eastern Chipmunk (6).

Please note that this is a private residence and I have used "Tottenville" as the location out of respect for the home owner's privacy.  For anyone doing data analysis, the Dickcissel is the same bird reported at Lisa Manne's feeders by Professor Dick Veit.

Rose-breasted Grosbeak - first observation of the season. Red-bellied--Woodpecker;Bluebird;Hairy Woodpecker;Cardinal;Hummingbird - all males.--Turkeys;Rose-breasted Grosbeak;Purple Finch - females. Cowbirds - 3 males, 2 females.  Red-winged Blackbirds - 7 males, 1 female.

The original eBird list only includes birds seen by TCL. Also reported were:--Common Nighthawk - 1--Ruby-crowned Kinglet (possible) - 1--American Pipit - 1--Northern Parula - 4--Bay-breasted Warbler - 1--"Baypoll" Warbler - 1--Mourning Warbler - 1 (male)--Connecticut Warbler - 1 (male seen in flight over the field)--House Sparrow - 1----Please adjust your list to align with the birds you remember observing.----Tom Johnson's post to CAYUGABIRDS---------Whew...After the stadium light banks were turned out just before 12:50 am, Mike Harvey, Tim Lenz, and I tallied up estimated (some are exact) counts for the evening.  ~42 species were recorded, with highlights in Upland Sandpiper, Cape May Warbler, Mourning Warbler, Connecticut Warbler, and Dickcissels.----These numbers are a mix of what we heard and saw... I should add that there were so many birds overhead that it was very difficult to mentally filter flight calls and look for birds on the ground/ in the trees... Most of the birds on the turf were Savannah Sparrows, with a few Bobolinks and Common Yellowthroats mixed in.  For a few notes on identifying birds visually at night... it can be quite tough to get good looks with the bright stadium lights providing intense unnatural illumination, but we had success in picking out Black-throated Blue Warblers, Canada Warblers, Northern Parulas, Ovenbirds, Magnolia Warblers, and a few others in flight.  However, for every bird I got a nice look at, countless others zipped by as brown and yellow blurs.----I recorded a good portion of the night's flight with a microphone sitting out on top of Mike Harvey's car... apparently the first couple of hours were not saved before my laptop battery died, so I need to work on recovering that file.  However, I have an hour and ten minutes of solid flight call insanity from the end of the evening's "stadium flight". During the majority of this time (11:30 pm - 12:40 am), we were hearing probably over 5 calls per second (potentially quite a few more than that). There was a noticeable dropoff in calling as soon as the lights were turned off, and within 5 minutes of the lights being shut off, we were--hearing single calls perhaps once every 3-5 seconds... the draw that the stadium lights have on migrants seems to be pretty amazing. Throughout the evening we kept hearing odd "tee-tee-tee-tee" calls that sounded reminiscent of both a woodpecker and a shorebird... we figured that they were probably Ruddy Turnstones, and comparison of two calls recorded tonight to turnstone recordings I have on my computer seems to support that.----I was pretty amazed by the number of birds dropping into and around the stadium tonight... highlights for me were the Upland Sandpiper that called as I was getting off my bike just after arriving at the stadium, great looks at the Cape May Warbler, and the mind-blowing flyby male Connecticut Warbler.  Thanks to the 14+ birders who came out and helped find birds...----TBJ

column47: One individual was observed swimming and diving alone.  The bird was obviously loon-shaped with a large, dark, dagger-like bill, large head and thick neck.  Body was large and dark above, white below.  It was about twice as large as nearby American Black Ducks (Anas rubripes).  ----The head was large, thought quite rounded relative to the squared-off, blocky heads of Common Loons (Gavia immer).  The forehead slopped gently into the culmen, not steep like on Common Loon.  The bill was smaller than Common Loons with less of a noticeable gonydeal angle.  ----Overall, the bird was dark gray above, white below.  Bill was gray.  Head, and especially the nape, was a ghostly silver-gray color, obviously paler than the crown and back.  The back was dark gray with obvious pale feather-edging.  A faint, but noticeable dark chin-strip was observed.  The neck line demarcating the dark dorsal and white ventral colors was sharp and straight.  There was no noticeable indentation of white as seen on Common Loons.  Dark feathers were observed all along the bird's flanks at the water's edge.  No white was visible as would be expected on an Arctic Loon (Gavia arctica). ----The bird was actively diving, staying under for about 30 seconds at a time.  It would surface for about 15 seconds, often many tens of meters from the previous dive location.  The diving style was quite different than what I am used to with Common Loons.  The bird would lunge quite high out of the water and make a big arch with its neck into the water.  In my experience, Common Loons tend to dip into water without such a concerted lunging effort.  No vocalizations were heard.  The bird was not seen flying or flapping/stretching it's wings. ----[Text copied from my NYSARC report.]

Sue and I and Kim Hartquist decided to walk a loop through the campground searching for sheltered places and hoping to hear more White-winged Crossbills after Andy Guthrie told us of 2 he had flying over on a walk to his car and back. It was quite breezy, making viewing and hearing birds somewhat difficult except in sheltered areas. There were LOTS of White-throated Sparrows, Red-breasted Nuthatches, and quite a few Purple Finches in the pines and the sheltered swales. There were also some campers, limiting the places I was willing to spish and do screech-owl whistles. At times there were so many birds inthe brush and treetops that actual counting all was impossible. The larger numbers are minimum totals, including some best estimates of large numbers coming in to spishing plus still in the distance calling.

The original eBird list only includes birds seen by TCL. Also reported were:--Common Nighthawk - 1--Ruby-crowned Kinglet (possible) - 1--American Pipit - 1--Northern Parula - 4--Bay-breasted Warbler - 1--"Baypoll" Warbler - 1--Mourning Warbler - 1 (male)--Connecticut Warbler - 1 (male seen in flight over the field)--House Sparrow - 1----Please adjust your list to align with the birds you remember observing.----Tom Johnson's post to CAYUGABIRDS---------Whew...After the stadium light banks were turned out just before 12:50 am, Mike Harvey, Tim Lenz, and I tallied up estimated (some are exact) counts for the evening.  ~42 species were recorded, with highlights in Upland Sandpiper, Cape May Warbler, Mourning Warbler, Connecticut Warbler, and Dickcissels.----These numbers are a mix of what we heard and saw... I should add that there were so many birds overhead that it was very difficult to mentally filter flight calls and look for birds on the ground/ in the trees... Most of the birds on the turf were Savannah Sparrows, with a few Bobolinks and Common Yellowthroats mixed in.  For a few notes on identifying birds visually at night... it can be quite tough to get good looks with the bright stadium lights providing intense unnatural illumination, but we had success in picking out Black-throated Blue Warblers, Canada Warblers, Northern Parulas, Ovenbirds, Magnolia Warblers, and a few others in flight.  However, for every bird I got a nice look at, countless others zipped by as brown and yellow blurs.----I recorded a good portion of the night's flight with a microphone sitting out on top of Mike Harvey's car... apparently the first couple of hours were not saved before my laptop battery died, so I need to work on recovering that file.  However, I have an hour and ten minutes of solid flight call insanity from the end of the evening's "stadium flight". During the majority of this time (11:30 pm - 12:40 am), we were hearing probably over 5 calls per second (potentially quite a few more than that). There was a noticeable dropoff in calling as soon as the lights were turned off, and within 5 minutes of the lights being shut off, we were--hearing single calls perhaps once every 3-5 seconds... the draw that the stadium lights have on migrants seems to be pretty amazing. Throughout the evening we kept hearing odd "tee-tee-tee-tee" calls that sounded reminiscent of both a woodpecker and a shorebird... we figured that they were probably Ruddy Turnstones, and comparison of two calls recorded tonight to turnstone recordings I have on my computer seems to support that.----I was pretty amazed by the number of birds dropping into and around the stadium tonight... highlights for me were the Upland Sandpiper that called as I was getting off my bike just after arriving at the stadium, great looks at the Cape May Warbler, and the mind-blowing flyby male Connecticut Warbler.  Thanks to the 14+ birders who came out and helped find birds...----TBJ

column23: Nate's Patch--Bluegrass to Hanshaw to Freese
column46: Overcast and snowing, snow light for much of the walk but wind and snow picked up significantly as we walked through the Equine Research Park; wind W at 10 mph; 32-30 F. There are shallow puddles (now frozen?) scattered across the field. The wheat in the field was harvested in mid July, leaving 6-12 inches of stubble, weeds, and grass in the field. Ground bare (no snow cover) when we began our walk, but there was a dusting of snow on the ground by the time that we returned to the house. Ponds (just north of Liddell Lab, and the small pond by the Equine Research Park) are open. Deciduous trees are bare. Casual observations while taking Rufus for a walk. We left home (1462 Hanshaw Road) and crossed south across the field to the northeast corner of the Equine Research Park woods. We walked along the eastern border of the woods; at the southeastern corner we turned east and walked southeast to view the pond just north of Liddell Lab. We then continued west along the east/west track that extends from Freese Road (at Liddell Lab) to the Equine Research Park, and walked west through the research park. We continued on north to Bluegrass Lane. At the northwest corner of the horse paddocks we turned east and walked along the north edge of the woods, before crossing the field back to the house. Sunday. Civil twilight begins 06:08; sunrise 06:36; sunset 18:00; civil twilight ends 18:28. Eastern Standard Time. Mammals: none observed.

column23: Hog Hole (Allan H. Treman State Marine Park)

column46: Clear (visibility 10.0 miles); wind variable at 5 mph to NW at 8 mph; 65-70 F. Sapsucker Woods Road and trails through the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary, from the south border of the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary just north of 67 Sapsucker Woods Road (excluding areas outside of the Sanctuary west of Sapsucker Woods Road, from Sanctuary Drive north to 260 Sapsucker Woods Road) north to the Cornell Lab of Ornithology. I entered the area around the "Frog Barn" (91 Sapsucker Woods Road), to as far as the Frog Barn pond. From the Frog Barn, I walked through the woods along the southwestern segment of the East Trail to Sapsucker Woods Road, crossed the road, and continued along the eastern segments of the Severinghaus and Wilson trails, including the boardwalk. At the Lab, I stepped into the observatory for a look at the pond and the bird feeding garden. I then stepped back outside the observatory and continued north, entering the Lab again at the staff entrance on the east side of the building. Monday. Civil twilight begins 04:59; sunrise 05:33; sunset 20:47; civil wilight ends 21:21.Eastern Daylight Saving Time. Mammals: Eastern Gray Squirrel (3), Red Squirrel (1), Eastern Chipmunk (8). The highlight were probably the Clapper Rail that was observed by the faithful remnant who returned to the bridge at the end of the walk, and the Kingfisher that did several flybys for our viewing.

DATE: Friday, 4 July 2003--LOCATION: Central Park - Turtle Pond--REPORTED BY: Ben Cacace <benc@nac.net>----Around 8:00pm I spotted a male Orchard Oriole while standing on the landing just below Belvedere Castle looking over Turtle Pond. The Orchard Oriole flew onto the rock below the castle. We (Denis and myself) were looking down at the bird. Over the next 15 minutes we got some excellent, looking down views without intervening foliage, as it foraged.----At 9:04p a Black Skimmer arrived on Turtle Pond. I watched it continuously before it left the pond around an hour and a half later at 10:35p.----** Total species - 21 **

column47: One adult seen feeding on a deer carcass about 200 yards out on the reservoir. It was feeding when I arrived and continued to until 11:07 pm. I did not see the eagle leave but at 11:15 pm I saw the eagle perched on the same white pine I had seen an eagle perched on yesterday. The eagle was actively feeding the whole time It was at the carcass. It would move around the cascade tugging at it here and there and also rip hair and pieces of hide off it. One to 3 crows were on the ground near the eagle and were apparently picking of scraps and cawing.

46 degrees, heavy dew, sunny.  Robins flying, and tried to keep track of count.  They were not in big flocks, but small groups, of 1, 3, 4, 1, 14, 7, 1.  Chickadee flew over just as we left the house, heard a crow.  Checked out Sarahpark, and nothing there, but as we got out on Sunset Meadow, 21 Canada geese flew from east to west in a single string.  Wasted a few minutes on a pair of starlings in OKP.  They were so far away, was trying to establish them as flickers, but turned out to be starlings.  Three crows were feeding in Long Meadow, when out of nowhere a crow appeared to be fleeing from an immature Northern Harrier, but it turned out they were just going in the same direction.  Crow flew on, hawk lit, crows in field were unconcerned.  On way home, heard a towhee in Sarahpark.  Birds were active there but couldn''t id any except the towhee who posed on a dead branch and called.  A couple of chickadees flew over, and a wren was playing on the fence around the oval.

Schulenberg home at 1462 Hanshaw Road. Clear (visibility 10 miles); wind E at 3 mph to S at 6 mph; 60-61 F. The corn in the field along Hanshaw Road is 6 feet tall, has developed tassels, and has ears of corn up to a foot long. The grass in the field at the corner of Freese and Hanshaw roads  was mowed on 16 July. There is a Prunus (chokecherry? black cherry?) in fruit at the edge of the woods behind Frank and Judy's house (1460 Hanshaw Road). Leaves of the east ash are turning yellow and dropping (already!). Casual observations from the driveway, from the back deck, from inside the woods behind the house (while playing the Black-capped Chickadee/Eastern Screech-Owl mobbing recording), and from inside the house looking out over the back yard and the bird feeders behind the house, and over the Cornell fields opposite to the house, across Hanshaw Road. Feeders up: sunflower (empty) and niger in the east maple, and safflower in the west maple; also hummingbird feeders in the east maple and under the eaves by the kitchen window. Friday. Civil twilight begins 06:01; sunrise 06:30; sunset 19:41; civil twilight ends 20:10. Eastern Daylight Saving Time. Mammals: Eastern Gray Squirrel (3), Red Squirrel (1),  Eastern Chipmunk (3| heard), Striped Skunk (1| I smelled skunk from the driveway when I first stepped outside; did not notice it later).

Full day's birding (Steve Kelling, Chris Wood, Brian Sullivan, Marshall Iliff) along Lake Ontario shore. In addition to Pine Grosbeaks and a few other nice surprises, there was an amazing movement of Canada Geese afoot. We noticed them after lunch only moving in a constant stream of hundreds coming across the lake and down from the NE. The only other species that showed obvious migratioon was Great Blue Heron--we saw about 6 that were flying high and clearly moving in this first major cold snap of the year.  WEATHER: Very cold (20-25 F), with strong (15-25 mph NW wind in exposed areas). Moderate snow in morning but clea for much of mid-day. A winter storm arriving that evening was probably part of the trigger of bird movement.

Twelve species of warblersa nice dayincluding two Nashville Warblers and two Northern Parulas, both ABA life birds, and a second Monroe County record of Brown Thrasher. I saw Nashville Warbler and Northern Parula two years ago in Bermuda. The migrating warblers flitted around, sometimes two or three species to a treeParula, Yellow, Black-throated Green, Black-throated Blue, and Redstartand sometimes eight or nine total.  Saw my first Barn Swallow of the year over the parking lot. A bunch of Brown Creepers7. Some other nice surprisesthree Blue-Gray Gnatcatchers, one of my favorites; Veery, at first I thought it was a Robin, chasing a Robin, but then saw its tawny good looks; a female Rose-breasted Grosbeak; a fiery male Blackburnian Warbler. Kildeer skittered up to truck. Pair feeding, one twittering to other and displaying rusty tail. Squatted once with undertail up.

column23: Salt Marsh Nature Center at Marine Park--Southwest
column46: In contrast to dismal weather forecasts, it was a beautiful warm and sunny morning on the West side of the creek, filled with the sights, sounds, scents, and activities of spring.  Birdsong, especially of Yellow Warblers, Red-Winged Blackbirds, and Northern Cardinals, filled the air, as did the heady scent of Autumn Olive blooms. Gorgeous Baltimore Oriole males seemed to be everywhere, some gathering nesting materials, and at least one cardinal chick was seen, hopping around its nest, under the watchful eye of Mom & Dad.  Special treats were our reunion with the Gerrittsen kildeer and the appearance of many butterflies, including Common Buckeyes, American Ladies, Red Admirals, and an extraordinary number of Eastern Tailed Blues, all posing for Mohammed''s camera.  Speaking of reunions, we were pleased to have Tom, on morning leave from baby Charlie, joining us on our walk, and finding us "good birds."
With Bob Guthrie.

column23: Salt Marsh Nature Center at Marine Park
column46: Ranger Christina led us through the new section on a truly glorious morning.  Bright hazy sun, no wind, mild temperatures - all helped us appreciate the site with a particularly high tide. Lots of ducks and geese paddling around among the new grasses. Highlights: wonderful views of a perched Red-tailed Hawk as well as action shots of it being bombed by a Kestrel, and later taking the initiative to drive off crows that looked threatening; lots of Buffleheads stirring up the water; more species of Sparrow than usually seen at this site - Song, White-throated, Savannah, Fox, and Swamp; a "standoff" between a Kestrel and a Mourning Dove, as they stood a foot apart on a rock eyeing each other; and a "fleet" of Red-breasted Mergansers swimming and diving like a chorus line.

Mostly cloudy (visibility 10 miles); wind S at 10 mph; 58 F. Sapsucker Woods Road and trails through the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary, from the south border of the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary just north of 67 Sapsucker Woods Road (excluding areas outside of the Sanctuary west of Sapsucker Woods Road, from Sanctuary Drive north to 260 Sapsucker Woods Road) north to the Cornell Lab of Ornithology. I entered the area around the "Frog Barn" (91 Sapsucker Woods Road), to as far as the Frog Barn pond. I then returned directly to Sapsucker Woods Road, and walked along the road north to Sapsucker Woods Pond and the Lab. I did not check for feeders at 143 and 151 Sapsucker Woods Road. At the Lab, I stepped into the observatory for a look at the pond and the bird feeding garden. Water levels on Sapsucker Woods Pond remain very low, with the scarcity of rain this summer. I stepped back outside the observatory, and continued north, entering the Lab at the staff entrance on the east side of the building. Friday. Civil twilight begins 06:25; sunrise 06:53; sunset 19:04; civil twilight ends 19:32. Eastern Daylight Saving Time. Mammals: Eastern Gray Squirrel (5), Eastern Chipmunk (10). Also: Bullfrog (x).

column23: Hamlin Beach SP--Parking Lot No. 4 (Primary Lakewatch site)
column46: Seemed like a good idea to see what a cool day with a stiff (15-20 mph) NW wind might bring.--    Basically little moving over the lake, but after a couple of hours, each time I was ready to leave at a half-hour point a burst of activity would keep me there.--    Essentially no waterfowl and NO shorebirds until 8:30, then all the shorebirds between then and 9:00. Scattered through, a few Bonaparte''s Gulls and Common Terns. The Forster''s Tern was first thing, headed east, where most birds were headed west.--    The swallow count is only birds going west and is again based on several 1 minute counts through the period averaged and then used with approx. percentages of migrants to reach totals. Suggests that yesterday''s estimates without counts were WAY LOW. Actually more swallows were headed east at each count period, but almost all of those were Bank, probably from the Devil''s Nose colony. Bigger percentage of Barn Swallows today, but actually more were going behind crossing the parking lot each time I headed out there than were in front, so not part of the total.----    Finally!!! a color-banded Caspian Tern on the beach!--
We left the house at 09:30 and were gone all day.  All woodpeckers - males.

column46: I took a walk around here, exploring the trails more thoroughly than we had on our Wednesday 13 May walk with Myrah. The YBFL was the obvious highlight, and the lowlight missing the male Golden-winged and the Bay-breasteds seen here the previous day.

Dense fog, beginning to lift after 09:00; calm; 27 F. Widespread frost on the ground. Civil twilight begins 06:34; sunrise 07:05.  Leaves of deciduous trees in the area are mostly bare. Sapsucker Woods Road and trails through the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary, from the south border of the Sapsucker Woods Sanctuary just north of 67 Sapsucker Woods Road (excluding areas outside of the Sanctuary west of Sapsucker Woods Road, from Sanctuary Drive north to 260 Sapsucker Woods Road) north to the Cornell Lab of Ornithology. I entered the area around the "Frog Barn" (91 Sapsucker Woods Road), to the edge of the Frog Barn pond. From the Frog Barn, I walked through the woods along the southwestern segment of the East Trail to Sapsucker Woods Road. I crossed the road, reentered the woods, and continued along the eastern segments of the Severinghaus and Wilson trails, including the boardwalk. Water levels on Sapsucker Woods Pond remain high (according to Charles Eldermire, the outlet to the pond is blocked, perhaps by a beaver); there is a thin crust of ice on the water in the back (southern) portions of the pond, especially in the wooded portion near the road. At the Lab, I stepped into the observatory for a quick look at the pond and the bird-feeding garden. I then stepped back and continued north, entering the Lab at the staff entrance at the northeast corner of the building. Tuesday. Eastern Standard Time. Mammals: Eastern Gray Squirrel (1), Red Squirrel (1).

column23: Salt Marsh Nature Center at Marine Park--Southwest
column46: In contrast to dismal weather forecasts, it was a beautiful warm and sunny morning on the West side of the creek, filled with the sights, sounds, scents, and activities of spring.  Birdsong, especially of Yellow Warblers, Red-Winged Blackbirds, and Northern Cardinals, filled the air, as did the heady scent of Autumn Olive blooms. Gorgeous Baltimore Oriole males seemed to be everywhere, some gathering nesting materials, and at least one cardinal chick was seen, hopping around its nest, under the watchful eye of Mom & Dad.  Special treats were our reunion with the Gerrittsen kildeer and the appearance of many butterflies, including Common Buckeyes, American Ladies, Red Admirals, and an extraordinary number of Eastern Tailed Blues, all posing for Mohammed''s camera.  Speaking of reunions, we were pleased to have Tom, on morning leave from baby Charlie, joining us on our walk, and finding us "good birds."
sunny, lw, 36
